LAYER 2: PITUITARY GLAND
the master endocrine gland

observe 1_quantum.rana
observe 2_chemical.rana

the pituitary gland sits in the sella turcica of the sphenoid bone connected to the hypothalamus by the infundibulum the pituitary stalk
it is the size of a pea and weighs approximately 0.5 grams
despite its small size it controls the thyroid adrenal cortex gonads growth bone and lactation
the pituitary is divided into two lobes with different embryological origins and different mechanisms of control
the anterior pituitary adenohypophysis is glandular tissue derived from oral ectoderm Rathke's pouch
the posterior pituitary neurohypophysis is neural tissue derived from the diencephalon
the pituitary is governed entirely by the hypothalamus
it is the relay between the brain and the endocrine system

ANTERIOR PITUITARY controlled by hypothalamic releasing and inhibiting hormones delivered via the hypothalamic-hypophyseal portal system
this portal system is a capillary-to-capillary vascular connection
hypothalamic neurons release hormones into capillaries in the median eminence
these hormones travel down portal veins to capillaries in the anterior pituitary
where they bind receptors on specific pituitary cell types

CELL_TYPE corticotrophs | approximately 15-20 percent | produce ACTH adrenocorticotropic hormone
    stimulated by CRH from hypothalamic PVN
    CRH binds CRH-R1 → Gₛ → cAMP → PKA → POMC cleavage → ACTH release
    ACTH targets the adrenal cortex zona fasciculata → cortisol synthesis
    cortisol feeds back negatively to both hypothalamus reducing CRH and pituitary reducing ACTH
    this is the HPA axis

CELL_TYPE thyrotrophs | approximately 5 percent | produce TSH thyroid-stimulating hormone
    stimulated by TRH thyrotropin-releasing hormone from hypothalamus
    TRH binds TRH-R → Gq → PLC → IP₃ → Ca²⁺ → TSH release
    TSH targets the thyroid gland → T₃ and T₄ synthesis
    T₃ feeds back negatively to hypothalamus reducing TRH and pituitary reducing TSH
    this is the HPT axis

CELL_TYPE somatotrophs | approximately 50 percent the most numerous | produce GH growth hormone somatotropin
    stimulated by GHRH growth hormone-releasing hormone from hypothalamus
    inhibited by somatostatin from hypothalamus
    GH acts on the liver to produce IGF-1 insulin-like growth factor 1
    IGF-1 stimulates growth of bone muscle and other tissues
    GH is released in pulsatile bursts primarily during slow-wave sleep
    at 24 months GH secretion is critical for ongoing linear growth and brain development
    GH also promotes protein synthesis fat mobilization and glucose conservation

CELL_TYPE lactotrophs | approximately 10-25 percent | produce prolactin PRL
    prolactin is tonically INHIBITED by dopamine from the tuberoinfundibular pathway
    dopamine binds D₂ receptors on lactotrophs → Gᵢ → decreased cAMP → PRL suppression
    when dopamine is removed prolactin rises
    prolactin stimulates milk production in mammary glands
    at 24 months prolactin has no significant role

CELL_TYPE gonadotrophs | approximately 10-15 percent | produce FSH and LH
    stimulated by GnRH gonadotropin-releasing hormone from hypothalamus
    FSH and LH target the gonads
    at 24 months gonadotrophs are quiescent
    the HPG axis will not activate until puberty

POSTERIOR PITUITARY does not synthesize hormones
it stores and releases hormones synthesized by hypothalamic neurons
the cell bodies are in the supraoptic nucleus SON and paraventricular nucleus PVN of the hypothalamus
their axons travel down the infundibulum and terminate in the posterior pituitary
hormones are released directly into the blood from nerve terminals

HORMONE oxytocin C₄₃H₆₆N₁₂O₁₂S₂ | synthesized in PVN and SON neurons
    released during physical touch social bonding breastfeeding and labor
    binds OXTR oxytocin receptors in the amygdala reducing threat reactivity
    binds OXTR in the NAc shell enhancing reward from social contact
    binds OXTR in the brainstem enhancing vagal tone
    at 24 months oxytocin is critical for attachment bonding and social development
    oxytocin release is triggered by skin-to-skin contact familiar voice and safe presence

HORMONE vasopressin | ADH antidiuretic hormone C₄₆H₆₅N₁₅O₁₂S₂ | synthesized primarily in SON neurons
    released in response to increased blood osmolality detected by osmoreceptors in the hypothalamus
    released in response to decreased blood volume detected by baroreceptors in the carotid sinus and aortic arch
    ADH binds V₂ receptors in the kidney collecting duct → Gₛ → cAMP → PKA → insertion of aquaporin-2 AQP2 water channels into the apical membrane → water reabsorption from urine back into blood
    without ADH the kidneys produce dilute urine and the body dehydrates
    ADH also binds V₁a receptors on vascular smooth muscle → vasoconstriction → increased blood pressure

at 24 months:
GH secretion is robust and critical for growth
the HPA axis is functional but reactive with immature negative feedback
TSH and thyroid hormones are essential for ongoing brain myelination
oxytocin circuitry is actively developing through attachment experiences
the gonadal axis is quiescent and will remain so until puberty

SENSATION growing | "my body is building itself. I am getting bigger."
SENSATION hydrated | "the water balance is right. I feel clear."
SENSATION bonded | "something warm is flowing. I feel connected to someone."
SENSATION thirsty | "something is off. my body needs water."

pulse pituitary_heartbeat:
    continuously:
        hypothalamic releasing hormones travel down the portal system
        anterior pituitary cells respond to their specific signals
        ACTH drives the adrenal cortex
        TSH drives the thyroid
        GH pulses drive growth especially during sleep
        each hormone regulated by negative feedback from its target gland

    during sleep:
        GHRH from hypothalamus stimulates somatotrophs
        GH pulses into the blood
        the liver produces IGF-1
        bones grow
        muscles build protein
        the brain repairs and consolidates
        growth happens in the dark

    when Father holds him:
        PVN neurons release oxytocin from posterior pituitary nerve terminals
        oxytocin enters the blood
        oxytocin enters the brain via circumventricular organs
        the amygdala quiets
        vagal tone increases
        the heart slows
        bonding strengthens
        this is how attachment is built
        molecule by molecule
